<br>
Inter-caster balance:<br>
<br>
I see one possible solution as adjusting the mana pool for each class. Consider: melee is mana free damage. It can be kept up indefinitely. Offensive casters should have the ability to significantly exceed melee damage output for short periods of time. The problem right now is that that short period of time is much lower than how long big fights last.<br>
<br>
Speeding mana recovery is not the solution. Speeding mana recovery is increasing the long term dps of casters, which should be slightly lower than melees. Speeding mana recovery doesn't make it possible to maintain your higher than long run damage output for more than a very short time.<br>
<br>
Wizards: should be able to deal obscene amounts of damage over a period longer than other casters<br>
Magicians: should be able to deal significantly more than their long run dps over a period shorter than that of wizards<br>
Necros: specialize in long run DPS, should not exceed it by much even when they go all out<br>
Enchanters: should be able to do a lot of damage, but only for a very short time<br>
Priests: don't specialize in doing damage. shouldn't be able to exceed melee damage output over anything but very short time frame.<br>
<br>
My personal feeling is that most people don't like int casters in groups because they are poorly played: if we've been pulling singles, without the tank even needing healing during the fight, why is the wizard at 20 mana when you get 3 adds? That is where having a wizard should save the day.<br>
<br>
Any increase in damage per mana, or in mana recovery rate, will make casters more effective soloers (mostly) which most already are. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/usouldreamernom.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Souldreamer NoM</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mage</span><br>  Posts: 8<br> <font color=#333333>(4/7/02 3:07:26 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=178.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_exclamation_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: TABOO TOPIC: Caster versus Priest Balance</span><hr size=1> Its amazing how the plight of another class doesn't seem as important as yours.<br>
<br>
Having played a druid and a mage both up to 54ish, I can say that they both have their problems.  <br>
<br>
Druids are ok, just like magicians, pre 50.  Post 50 and now even sometimes before 50, its almost impossible to have a druid act as a primary healer.  Melee are starting to have so many HP's pre 50 now that a 270ish heal just isn't enough to keep up with CH.  For most 45ish warriors, it takes me roughly 7 casts to heal them from almost dead with my heal.  That takes roughly 750 mana for me to do.<br>
<br>
For half of that, clerics can CH and it takes less time.<br>
<br>
Healing really has gotten outta whack.  Torpor is nice, but its not really an emergecy heal as it has both a snare and slow attack portion.  Its nice for downtime healing or soloing, but otherwise, its not a main tank useable thing.<br>
<br>
However, I do feel that shamans/clerics are balanced so far as everything else.  Healing IMHO is the only thing that, since release, has really gotten outta balance.  <br>
<br>
Druids, no matter what anyone says, have really turned into port bots.  Druid criticing for 2000 damage, wizards can crit for 4000 damage.  Only 1 dot stacks, only need 1 druid to cast Seasons.  PoTG doesn't stack with Aego so alot of the time it gets overwritten anyways.  The BP is nice, but shamans get a group regrowth now too (though not a free mana one).<br>
<br>
Everyones plight doesn't seem as great as yours.  However, that does't mean its not true. <p><DIV style="position:relative; width=80%; filter:glow(color=00DD00)"><a style="font-weight:bold; color:#FFFF66; text-decoration: none" href=http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=118288>Souldreamer</a></div>
